SIMPLE: trustee
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trustee
<hw>Trus*tee"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A
person to whom property is legally committed in trust, to be applied
either for the benefit of specified individuals, or for public uses; one
who is intrusted with property for the benefit of another; also, a
person in whose hands the effects of another are attached in a trustee
process.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Trustee process</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a process
by which a creditor may attach his debtor's goods, effects, and credits,
in the hands of a third person; -- called, in some States, the
<altname>process of foreign attachment</altname>,
<altname>garnishment</altname>, or <altname>factorizing
process</altname>.</cd> <mark>[U. S.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trustee</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trustee
<hw>Trus*tee"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
commit (property) to the care of a trustee; <as>as, to <ex>trustee</ex>
an estate</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To attach (a debtor's wages,
credits, or property in the hands of a third person) in the interest of
the creditor.</def> <mark>[U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trustee process</ent>⟦br⟧
